ggplot graph: Visitors to Channel Islands NP

gg_base <- ggplot2::ggplot(data = ci_np, aes(x = year, y = visitors)) 
  gg_base +
  geom_area()

  gg_base +
  geom_line(
    color = "purple",
    linetype = "dashed"
  )

  gg_base + 
  geom_point(color = "purple",
             pch = 17,
             size = 4,
             alpha = 0.5)

  gg_base + 
  geom_point(
    aes(size = visitors,
        color = visitors),
    alpha = 0.5
  )

  gg_base + 
  geom_col(aes(fill = visitors))

  gg_base +
  geom_point(
    aes(size = visitors,
        color = visitors),
    alpha = 0.5
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

  gg_base +
  geom_line(linetype = "dotted") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(
    x = "Year",
    y = "Annual park visitors",
    title = "Channel Islands NP Visitation",
    subtitle = "(1963 - 2016)"
  ) + scale_y_continuous(labels=comma) 

  gg_base +
  geom_line(color = "purple") +
  geom_point(color = "orange",
             aes(size = year),
             alpha = 0.5)

  gg_base +
  geom_col(fill = "orange",
           color = "purple") +
  geom_line(color = "green")

Now plotting multiple series

gg_np <- ggplot(data = ca_np, aes(x = year, y = visitors, group = park_name))
gg_np + geom_line(aes(color = park_name)) 

gg_np +
  geom_line(show.legend = FALSE) +
  theme_light() + 
  labs(x = "year", y = "annual visitors") +
  facet_wrap(~ park_name)

Exporting a ggplot graph with ggsave() ggsave() will export the most recently run ggplot graph by default (plot = last_plot()), unless you give it the name of a different saved ggplot object. Some common arguments for ggsave():

ggsave(here("figures", "np_graph.jpg"), dpi = 180, width = 8, height = 7)
